&lt;h3>
    &lt;a id=&quot;User-Experience View&quot; name=&quot;User-Experience View&quot;>User-Experience View&lt;/a>
&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>
    This section describes the architecturally significant elements of the User-Experience Model.
&lt;/p>
&lt;h4>
    &lt;a id=&quot;Overview&quot; name=&quot;Overview&quot;>Overview&lt;/a>
&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>
    The User-Experience Model captures a very important part of the PearlCircle specification. It captures the screens
    presented to the user and the transitions between screens resulting from user-generated events such as clicking on a
    link or a button on a form. Screen descriptions also contain descriptions of the dynamic content that the system must
    produce and display to the user.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    The User-Experience Model consists of:
&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
    &lt;li>
        User-Experience Elements (e.g., screens and input forms), organized by business packages, as well as a Common
        package that contains those elements that are common to all User-Experience Storyboards (e.g., the home screen).
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        User-Experience Model Storyboards that describe navigation between the User-Experience Elements that participate in
        the individual Use-Cases, organized by business area.
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        Navigation Maps that describe the navigation amongst the application User-Experience Elements (one navigation map
        per business package).
    &lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>
    The structure of the PearlCircle User-Experience Model is shown below:
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    &lt;img height=&quot;162&quot; src=&quot;resources/uxmodelexplorer.gif&quot; alt=&quot;digram showing nested folders&quot; width=&quot;271&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; />
&lt;/p>
&lt;h4>
    &lt;a id=&quot;Navigation Map&quot; name=&quot;Navigation Map&quot;>Navigation Map&lt;/a>
&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>
    A Navigation Map is a class diagram showing the navigation paths between selected User-Experience Elements (e.g.,
    screens and input forms).
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    The following diagram shows the User-Experience Elements and the navigation paths for the key User Account Management
    use-cases (the diagram can be found in User-Experience Model::Ux Model Elements::User Account Management package).
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    &lt;img height=&quot;798&quot; src=&quot;resources/user_acct_mgmt_navmap.gif&quot; alt=&quot;digram described in accompanying text&quot; width=&quot;1336&quot;
    border=&quot;0&quot; />
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    There can be multiple Navigation Map diagrams. In fact, for PearlCircle, a Navigation Map is defined for each of the
    business packages.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    The classes on the diagram represent (1) screens (stereotyped &amp;lt;&amp;lt;screen&amp;gt;&amp;gt;), (2) input forms (stereotyped
    &amp;lt;&amp;lt;input form&amp;gt;&amp;gt;) or (3) dynamic content bundles, whose content is displayed on the screens or in the input
    forms (no stereotype).
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    The relationships between the &amp;lt;&amp;lt;screen&amp;gt;&amp;gt; classes represent navigation paths between the screens that are
    initiated by the user's actions. The user actions are represented by the operations on the screens. The dynamic content
    displayed on the screens is represented by the attributes on the screens.
&lt;/p>
&lt;h4>
    &lt;a id=&quot;Architecturally Significant Storyboards&quot; name=&quot;Architecturally Significant Storyboards&quot;>Architecturally
    Significant Storyboards&lt;/a>
&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>
    Each Use Case has its own &quot;storyboard&quot;. A User-Experience Storyboard is a synthesis of the User-Experience Elements
    that participate in the realization of a Use Case. In other words, a User-Experience Storyboard shows system behavior
    from the User-Experience Model perspective. As an example, the following diagrams show the participants and the basic
    flow of the Create Auction User-Experience Storyboard (the User-Experience Storyboards for the remaining
    architecturally-significant Use Cases can be found in the User-Experience Model).
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    &lt;img height=&quot;787&quot; src=&quot;resources/create_auction_participants.gif&quot; alt=&quot;digram described in accompanying text&quot;
    width=&quot;1217&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; />
&lt;/p>
&lt;br />
&lt;p>
    Note: User-Experience Storyboard participants diagrams can be considered &quot;mini Navigation Maps&quot; for the Use Case.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    &lt;img height=&quot;777&quot; src=&quot;resources/create_auction_basic_flow.gif&quot; alt=&quot;digram described in accompanying text&quot;
    width=&quot;1693&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; />
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
    The basic flow of the above User-Experience Storyboard can be summarized as follows:
&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
    &lt;li>
        The system presents the Seller with the &lt;b>account home&lt;/b> screen, which contains a URL to create a new auction.
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        The Seller inputs auction information into the &lt;b>auction info form&lt;/b> input form.
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        The system displays the entered auction information for the Seller to confirm (in the &lt;b>auction info
        confirmation&lt;/b> screen).
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        The Seller confirms the auction information.
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        The system displays the credit information on file (in the &lt;b>auction payment info&lt;/b> screen) and asks the Seller
        if he/she want to use the card &quot;on file&quot; to pay for the auction.
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        The Seller has the option to accept the on file credit card information or input new credit card information (in
        the &lt;b>auction payment&lt;/b> form).
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        The system verifies entered credit information and displays the &lt;b>account creation success&lt;/b> screen
    &lt;/li>
&lt;/ul></mainDescription>
